title: What to do if you become disabled

heading_context: What to do if you become disabled
chunks.html_content:
You have rights if you become disabled to protect you from discrimination. You might also be entitled to certain benefits.

The main disability and sickness benefits are:

  • Disability Living Allowance (DLA) or Personal Independence Payment (PIP)
  • Attendance Allowance
  • Employment and Support Allowance (ESA)

What you’re entitled to depends on your circumstances - use a benefits calculator to see what you might be able to get.

You might also be able to get:

  • certain types of equipment or have adaptations made to your home without paying VAT
  • Council Tax discounts
  • a TV licence discount
  • free vehicle tax

heading_context: What to do if you become disabled
chunks.html_content: If you’re in England you can get a health and social care assessment to find out what help you can get (for example equipment, home care, day centres) from your local council.
chunks.plain_content:
What to do if you become disabled
If you’re in England you can get a health and social care assessment to find out what help you can get (for example equipment, home care, day centres) from your local council.

heading_context: What to do if you become disabled
chunks.html_content:
Your employer cannot discriminate against you because of your disability - you’re protected by the Equality Act 2010.

They must also keep your job open for you and cannot put pressure on you to resign just because you’ve become disabled.

Your employer must make ‘reasonable adjustments’ for you so that you’re not disadvantaged compared to non-disabled people.

This could include:

  • a phased return to work, for example working flexible hours or part-time
  • time off for medical treatment or counselling
  • giving another employee tasks you cannot easily do
  • providing practical aids and technical equipment for you

What to do if you become disabled
Reasonable adjustments

heading_context: What to do if you become disabled
Get help from Access to Work
chunks.html_content:
If the help you need at work is not covered by your employer making reasonable adjustments, you may be able to get help from Access to Work.

An Access to Work grant can pay for:

  • special equipment, adaptations or support worker services to help you do things like answer the phone or go to meetings
  • help getting to and from work
  • mental health support
  • communication support at a job interview (for example, a British Sign Language interpreter or a lipspeaker)

heading_context: What to do if you become disabled
chunks.html_content:
If you’re an employee and cannot work because of your disability, you may be able to get Statutory Sick Pay (SSP). Some employers have their own sick pay scheme instead.

If you still cannot work after 28 weeks, or you cannot get Statutory Sick Pay, you can apply for Universal Credit or Employment and Support Allowance (ESA).

Time off from work should not be recorded as an ‘absence from work’ if you’re waiting for your employer to put reasonable adjustments in place.

heading_context: What to do if you become disabled
chunks.html_content: Check your employment status if you’re not sure whether you’re an employee or not.

heading_context: What to do if you become disabled
chunks.html_content:
Your employer cannot dismiss you just because you’ve become disabled.

You can be dismissed if your disability means you cannot do your job even with reasonable adjustments.

You cannot be selected for redundancy just because you’re disabled.
chunks.plain_content:
What to do if you become disabled
Dismissals and redundancy
Your employer cannot dismiss you just because you’ve become disabled.
You can be dismissed if your disability means you cannot do your job even with reasonable adjustments.
You cannot be selected for redundancy just because you’re disabled.

heading_context: What to do if you become disabled
chunks.html_content: For advice about work issues, talk to Acas (the Advisory, Conciliation and Arbitration Service), Citizens Advice or your trade union representative.
